('', 'MenuFX Guide', 'menufx-guide', '', '<h2>Horizontal Navigation</h2>\r\n<p>The horizontal navigation refers to the top navigation, that uses the core Joomla! menu module, assigned to the <strong>"user3"</strong> module position. There are four different menu types that can be used in the <strong>topnav</strong> block.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Horizontal -&gt; Default</h3>\r\n<p>This is the default state of the top navigation and will be styled as a traditional horizontal menu bar with no sub items, something like the image below. If you installed with the sample data within configurator, then you will not need to change anything, how.</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/default-topnav.png" alt="">\r\n\r\n<p>Using the default menu</p>\r\n<p>If your menu does not look like the image above then its probably a difference between your menu modules parameter settings and what Morph needs. First thing to do is check your parameters to see that they match the below requirements.</p>\r\n	\r\n<h4>1. Check module parameter settings</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Menu name: the name of the menu you want to load</li>\r\n	<li>Menu style: list</li>\r\n	<li>Start Level: 0</li>\r\n	<li>End Level: 0 (unless you are using a the split menu then this needs to be 1 or 2)</li>\r\n	<li>Show sub items: No</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting morph framework for Joomla menu parameters" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/images/snaps/nomenu-params.png" alt="Menu parameters" width="659" height="157">\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Check advanced Parameter settings</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Menu Suffix: there should be no suffix set</li>\r\n	<li>Module Suffix: there should be no suffix set</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<img title="set menu class suffix for setting up your joomla menu" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/nomenu-sfx.png" alt="set menu class suffix for setting up your joomla menu" width="659" height="52">\r\n\r\n<h3>Horizontal -&gt; SubText</h3>\r\n<p>Subtext is a feature that allows you to add an additional line of text underneath the main menu item to provide more meaning as seen in the below example.</p>\r\n\r\n<img title="how the default horizontal menu in morph template for Joomla looks" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/images/snaps/horz-subtext.png" alt="how the default horizontal menu in morph for Joomla looks" width="659" height="66">\r\n\r\n<h4>Using subtext</h4>\r\n<p>Step 1: Adding a module suffix of "<strong>subtext</strong>" will allow you to use subtext in your menu items.Note, you can also add the same effect to any of the different levels in your menu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting a suffix for subtext in a joomla menu" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/subtext-sfx.png" alt="setting a suffix for subtext in a joomla menu" width="659" height="50"></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: Open the menu in the Joomla admin by hovering over the "Menus" option at the top and then selecting the menu you will add subtext to. Now you will need to update you menu items with the subtext you want. The subtext is added to the menu name after you add a "#" An example of this would be Home#my main page. Notice how the # is used set the breaking point for the subtext. Don''t worry, the # will not be included in your menu items, here is an example of how it should look.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting up subtext menu in Joomla and Morph" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/setting-menu-subitems.png" alt="setting up subtext menu in Joomla and Morph" width="659" height="29"></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Want to use subtext with sub menu items?</h4>\r\n<p>This scenario does not include sub items, however subtext can be used with sub items as well. This is done by adding the suffix of <strong>"subtext"</strong> along with either of the <strong>"topfish"</strong> and <strong>"topdrop"</strong> menus which are explained below.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>Horizontal -&gt; Superfish (topfish)</h3>\r\n<p>The topfish "aka superfish" menu allows you to have sub items in your menu up to 4 levels deep, the sub levels slide out below the parent item with all sub items sliding out to the side, here is an example image.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting up the top suckerfish superfish menu in a joomla template" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/topfish.png" alt="setting up the top suckerfish superfish menu in a joomla template" width="659" height="146"></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Using subtext</h4>\r\n<p>Step 1: Adding a module suffix of "<strong>topfish</strong>" will activate the top horizontal Superfish navigation.</p>\r\n<p><img title="adding the suffix in Joomla admin for top superdrop menu" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/topfish-sfx.png" alt="adding the suffix in Joomla admin for top superdrop menu"></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: Make sure your menu is set to show sub items</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting the sub menu items to show" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/show-sub-yes.png" alt="setting the sub menu items to show" width="659" height="36"></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>Horizontal -&gt; Dropline (topdrop)</h3>\r\n<p>The topdrop "aka dropline" menu puts the second level menu items in a sub bar, under the main menu items. All further sub items will drop down like the above superfish menu. This allows you to get the best of both worlds, you can see an example in the image below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="setting up the topdrop menu navigation in a joomla template" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/topdrop.png" alt="setting up the topdrop menu in a joomla template" width="660" height="164"></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 1: Adding a module suffix of "<strong>topdrop</strong>" will activate the top dropline menu with a twist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img title="adding the suffix in Joomla admin for top superdrop menu" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/topdrop-sfx.png" alt="adding the suffix in Joomla admin for top superdrop menu" width="659" height="51"></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step 2: Make sure your menu is set to show sub items</p>\r\n<img title="setting the sub menu items to show" src="http://www.joomlajunkie.com/morph/documentation/wp-content/uploads/docimages/show-sub-yes.png" alt="setting the sub menu items to show" width="659" height="36">\r\n\r\n<h3>Horizontal &amp; Vertical -&gt; Split Menu</h3>\r\n<p>The split menu is a very handy menu indeed and it allows you to use both top and side navigation in combination with one another. For websites with navigation that has many levels of menu items, this menu can help make the navigation easier. As the name suggests, the menu items are split between both top and sidebar navigations. However, they work together as int he top menu will shoiw first level items and the side will show the This is achieved by showing a certain.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>Combining menu suffixes</h3>\r\n\r\n<h4>Horizontal -&gt; TopDrop with subtext</h4>\r\n<p>split menu requires a few changes to your mainmenu modules settings. More info coming soon.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Horizontal -&gt; Topfish with subtext</h4>\r\n\r\n<h3>2. Vertical Navigation:</h3>\r\n<p>Default - This is the default state of the sidebar navigation and will be styled as a traditional vertical menu. The default state requires no module suffixes. Any sub menu items will be displayed as a nested list with this option.SubtextAs with the horizontal navigation, adding a module suffix of "subtext" will allow you to use subtext in your vertical menu items. Again, this can be used on any of the different menu levels. Once you have added the module suffix to your menu module, you will need to update you menu items to use subtext. An example of this would be Home#This is my subtext. Notice how the # is used set the breaking point for the subtext. Don''t worry, the # will not be included in your menu items.SideFishAdding a module suffix of "<strong>sidefish</strong>" will activate the sidebar vertical Superfish navigation. Once you have added the menu''s module suffix, you can proceed to add child menu items to your navigation. See below if you are not sure how to add child (sub) menu items to your menu. Depending on which sidebar the menu is published will determine how the sub items will fly out.</p>', '', -2, 1, 0, 3, '2009-07-12 09:07:53', 62, 'Morph', '2009-07-12 11:22:42', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-07-12 09:07:53', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 0, '', '', 2, 0, 'robots=\nauthor=') ,
